      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "**Features decreasing hERG risk**\n- **Carboxylic acid (anionic at pH 7.4):** introduces strong polarity and often reduces passive membrane partitioning into the channel cavity; can also reduce the *effective* fraction of the molecule that is monocationic (zwitterion formation).\n- **High polarity / multiple heteroatoms:** tends to reduce hERG affinity versus lipophilic cationic scaffolds.\n- **Rigid, compact 3D scaffold:** many potent hERG blockers benefit from **a spatial arrangement of hydrophobes flanking a basic center** with a geometry that fits the cavity. A rigid polycyclic system can either help (if it matches) or hurt (if it doesn\u2019t). Here, the presence of a **carboxylate and multiple carbonyls** suggests the scaffold is not optimized for the classic hERG pharmacophore.",
